<paragraph blockId="86.[151,1436,192,1658]" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">
<emphasis box="[198,301,1472,1497]" italics="true" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">Remarks</emphasis>
. This is the first description of the male of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fox" authorityYear="1894" box="[820,933,1472,1497]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Sphaerophthalma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="86" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scaber">
<emphasis box="[820,933,1472,1497]" italics="true" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">D. scaber</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Both sexes key very easily. This species belongs to the species Group 
<emphasis box="[496,579,1512,1537]" italics="true" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">Scabra</emphasis>
, in which both sexes have the sides and apex of sternum II scabrous, and the posterior trochanters of the male are produced at the apex internally into a blunt tooth. The sex association is made on the basis of collection data, distribution, and external morphology. This is a relatively uncommon species of which about an equal number of females have been examined.
</paragraph>
